---
import { Picture } from 'astro:assets';
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import technicalBlueprint from '../assets/images/technical-blueprint.jpg';
---

<BaseLayout
    title="Capping Chuck Glossary | Torque, Knurling, Thread Pitch, and More"
    description="Definitions for capping chuck and headset terminology: knurling, thread pitch, top load, static torque, slip torque, bridge count, closure ovalization."
    canonical="https://cappingchucks.com/glossary/"
    ogTitle="Glossary | CappingChucks.com"
    ogDescription="Capping terminology defined: knurling, torque, thread pitch, top load, slip torque, bridge count, and closure ovalization."
    breadcrumb="Glossary"
>
    <header class="pt-20 pb-12 border-b border-border">
        <div class="mx-auto max-w-3xl px-6 pb-4">
            <p class="font-mono text-[0.7rem] text-teal-700 tracking-wider uppercase mb-2"><a href="/" class="no-underline hover:underline">Home</a> / Glossary</p>
            <h1 class="mb-4">Glossary</h1>
            <p class="text-lg text-ink-light leading-relaxed max-w-xl">Technical terms used in capping chuck and <a href="/capping-headsets/">headset</a> specifications, calibration, and troubleshooting.</p>
        </div>
        <figure class="mx-auto max-w-4xl px-6">
            <Picture
                src={technicalBlueprint}
                alt="Engineering blueprint with compass and pencil showing cross-section drawings of machined components"
                class="w-full h-56 sm:h-72 object-cover object-center rounded-lg"
                widths={[600, 900, 1200]}
                sizes="100vw"
                formats={['avif', 'webp']}
                quality={80}
                loading="eager"
            />
            <figcaption class="mt-2 font-mono text-[0.68rem] text-ink-faint">Technical drawing of precision machined components. Photo: Pexels</figcaption>
        </figure>
    </header>

    <main>
        <section class="py-16 border-b border-border">
            <div class="mx-auto max-w-3xl px-6">
                <dl>
                    <div class="gloss-entry" id="knurling">
                        <dt class="gloss-term">Knurling</dt>
                        <dd class="gloss-def">A pattern of raised diamond or straight-line ridges on the outside of a closure shell. This is what the <a href="/chuck-types/">chuck</a> grips during torque application. Knurl pitch and depth have to match between chuck insert and closure, or you get slippage or <a href="/troubleshooting/">scuffing</a>.</dd>
                    </div>
                    <div class="gloss-entry" id="thread-pitch">
                        <dt class="gloss-term">Thread Pitch</dt>
                        <dd class="gloss-def">The axial distance between adjacent thread crests, measured in millimeters per revolution. Standard beverage closure pitches run from 3.0mm to 6.35mm (see <a href="https://www.isbt.com/resources/isbt-threadspecs" rel="noopener" target="_blank">ISBT voluntary threadspecs</a>). Pitch determines how many rotations you need for full engagement and directly affects the relationship between application torque and axial seal compression.</dd>
                    </div>
                    <div class="gloss-entry" id="top-load">
                        <dt class="gloss-term">Top Load</dt>
                        <dd class="gloss-def">Axial compressive force applied by the chuck onto the closure's top panel during application, measured in Newtons. Top load compresses the internal liner against the container finish sealing surface. Too much deforms thin-wall closures. Too little means poor seal integrity and vacuum loss.</dd>
                    </div>
                    <div class="gloss-entry" id="static-torque">
                        <dt class="gloss-term">Static Torque</dt>
                        <dd class="gloss-def">The torque needed to start loosening a closure that has been applied and allowed to rest. Measured with a calibrated torque analyzer. Typically 10 to 30% lower than the original application torque due to liner relaxation and friction decay at the thread interface. Primary QC metric for closure integrity audits.</dd>
                    </div>
                    <div class="gloss-entry" id="slip-torque">
                        <dt class="gloss-term">Slip Torque</dt>
                        <dd class="gloss-def">The torque threshold where the <a href="/capping-headsets/">headset's</a> clutch mechanism disengages and allows free rotation between drive spindle and closure. This sets the maximum torque the headset can deliver. It needs to sit above target application torque but below the closure's structural failure point.</dd>
                    </div>
                    <div class="gloss-entry" id="bridge-count">
                        <dt class="gloss-term">Bridge Count (TE Band)</dt>
                        <dd class="gloss-def">Number of frangible plastic bridges connecting the tamper-evident band to the closure body, typically 6 to 12 per closure. Bridge count determines how much force is needed to separate the band at first opening. During capping, the chuck has to seat the closure fully without <a href="/troubleshooting/">fracturing bridges prematurely</a>.</dd>
                    </div>
                    <div class="gloss-entry" id="closure-ovalization">
                        <dt class="gloss-term">Closure Ovalization</dt>
                        <dd class="gloss-def">A dimensional defect where the closure's round cross-section goes elliptical. Caused by excessive chuck grip force, bad stacking in storage, or thin-wall molding tolerance issues. Ovalized closures don't engage threads evenly, leading to cross-threading, torque scatter, and compromised seals. Allowable ovality is typically &plusmn;0.2 mm on nominal OD, per the closure supplier's spec.</dd>
                    </div>
                </dl>

                <div class="callout mt-8">
                    Use the closure supplier's current torque-test method and any applicable customer, regulatory, or industry specifications when setting validation criteria. <a href="https://store.astm.org/d2063_d2063m-24.html" rel="noopener" target="_blank">ASTM D2063</a> covers torque retention measurement for threaded closures.
                </div>
            </div>
        </section>

        <section class="py-16 border-b border-border">
            <div class="mx-auto max-w-3xl px-6">
                <span class="section-rule"></span>
                <h2 class="mb-4">Industry Resources</h2>
                <p class="text-[0.92rem] text-ink-light mb-6">Standards bodies, trade organizations, and regulatory references relevant to capping and closure work.</p>
                <ul class="space-y-3 text-[0.92rem]">
                    <li><a href="https://www.isbt.com/" rel="noopener" target="_blank">ISBT</a> -- International Society of Beverage Technologists. Maintains the <a href="https://www.isbt.com/resources/isbt-threadspecs" rel="noopener" target="_blank">voluntary threadspecs</a> (PCO 1881, 1810, etc.) used across the beverage industry.</li>
                    <li><a href="https://www.pmmi.org/" rel="noopener" target="_blank">PMMI</a> -- The Association for Packaging and Processing Technologies. Trade association for packaging machinery manufacturers.</li>
                    <li><a href="https://store.astm.org/d2063_d2063m-24.html" rel="noopener" target="_blank">ASTM D2063</a> -- Standard test methods for torque retention measurement on threaded closures (current revision, 2024).</li>
                    <li><a href="https://www.ecfr.gov/current/title-16/chapter-II/subchapter-E/part-1700" rel="noopener" target="_blank">16 CFR Part 1700</a> -- CPSC regulation governing child-resistant packaging in the United States.</li>
                    <li><a href="https://eur-lex.europa.eu/eli/dir/2019/904/oj" rel="noopener" target="_blank">EU Directive 2019/904</a> -- Single-Use Plastics Directive requiring tethered closures on certain beverage containers.</li>
                </ul>
            </div>
        </section>

        <section class="py-16 pb-20">
            <div class="mx-auto max-w-3xl px-6">
                <span class="section-rule"></span>
                <h2 class="mb-4">Related</h2>
                <ul class="space-y-3 text-[0.92rem]">
                    <li><a href="/chuck-types/">Capping Chuck Types</a> -- where these terms get applied</li>
                    <li><a href="/capping-headsets/">Capping Headsets</a> -- torque delivery and slip torque in practice</li>
                    <li><a href="/troubleshooting/">Troubleshooting & Calibration</a> -- using these specs to diagnose issues</li>
                </ul>
            </div>
        </section>
    </main>
</BaseLayout>
